<p>The segregation strengths in the compressible approach can be monitored through a proper effective Flory–Huggins 
 <italic>χ</italic> that carries its dependence not only on temperature but also on pressure. It has been suggested in our previous works that 
 <italic>χ</italic> consists of two terms as 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm64">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>χ</mi>
     <mo>=</mo>
     <msub>
      <mi>χ</mi>
      <mi>H</mi>
     </msub>
     <mo>+</mo>
     <msub>
      <mi>χ</mi>
      <mi>S</mi>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> [
 <xref rid="B34-polymers-11-01081" ref-type="bibr">34</xref>,
 <xref rid="B35-polymers-11-01081" ref-type="bibr">35</xref>]. The former 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm65">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mi>χ</mi>
      <mi>H</mi>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> (=
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm66">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>β</mi>
     <mo>Δ</mo>
     <mover accent="true">
      <mi>ε</mi>
      <mo>¯</mo>
     </mover>
     <mo>⋅</mo>
     <mrow>
      <mo>|</mo>
      <mrow>
       <mi>u</mi>
       <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
       <mi>η</mi>
       <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
      </mrow>
      <mo>|</mo>
     </mrow>
     <mo>/</mo>
     <mn>2</mn>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>) indicates the conventional enthalpic term with density dependence, where 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm67">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mo>Δ</mo>
     <mover accent="true">
      <mi>ε</mi>
      <mo>¯</mo>
     </mover>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> is the exchange energy between 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm68">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mover accent="true">
       <mi>ε</mi>
       <mo>¯</mo>
      </mover>
      <mrow>
       <mi>i</mi>
       <mi>j</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>’s as 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm69">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mo>Δ</mo>
     <mover accent="true">
      <mi>ε</mi>
      <mo>¯</mo>
     </mover>
     <mo>≡</mo>
     <msub>
      <mover accent="true">
       <mi>ε</mi>
       <mo>¯</mo>
      </mover>
      <mrow>
       <mi>i</mi>
       <mi>i</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
     <mo>+</mo>
     <msub>
      <mover accent="true">
       <mi>ε</mi>
       <mo>¯</mo>
      </mover>
      <mrow>
       <mi>j</mi>
       <mi>j</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
     <mo>−</mo>
     <mn>2</mn>
     <msub>
      <mover accent="true">
       <mi>ε</mi>
       <mo>¯</mo>
      </mover>
      <mrow>
       <mi>i</mi>
       <mi>j</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>. The latter 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm70">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mi>χ</mi>
      <mi>S</mi>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> (=
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm71">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msubsup>
      <mi>P</mi>
      <mi>φ</mi>
      <mn>2</mn>
     </msubsup>
     <mi mathvariant="normal">v</mi>
     <mo>*</mo>
     <mo>/</mo>
     <mn>2</mn>
     <mi>k</mi>
     <mi>T</mi>
     <mi>η</mi>
     <msub>
      <mi>B</mi>
      <mi>T</mi>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>) indicates the entropic term, where 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm72">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msubsup>
      <mi>P</mi>
      <mi>ϕ</mi>
      <mrow/>
     </msubsup>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> is the composition coefficient of pressure as 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm73">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msubsup>
      <mi>P</mi>
      <mi>ϕ</mi>
      <mrow/>
     </msubsup>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm74">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mo>≡</mo>
     <msub>
      <mrow>
       <mrow>
        <mrow>
         <mo>∂</mo>
         <mi>P</mi>
         <mo>/</mo>
         <mo>∂</mo>
         <mi>ϕ</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>)</mo>
       </mrow>
      </mrow>
      <mrow>
       <mi>T</mi>
       <mo>,</mo>
       <mi mathvariant="normal">v</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> and 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm75">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mi>B</mi>
      <mi>T</mi>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> is the bulk modulus as 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm76">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mi>B</mi>
      <mi>T</mi>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm77">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mo>≡</mo>
     <mi>η</mi>
     <mo>⋅</mo>
     <mo>∂</mo>
     <mi>P</mi>
     <mo>/</mo>
     <mo>∂</mo>
     <mi>η</mi>
     <msub>
      <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
      <mrow>
       <mi>T</mi>
       <mo>,</mo>
       <mi>ϕ</mi>
       <mo>’</mo>
       <mi>s</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>. 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm78">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msubsup>
      <mi>P</mi>
      <mi>ϕ</mi>
      <mrow/>
     </msubsup>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> gives the compressibility difference between components as 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm79">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mi>P</mi>
      <mi>φ</mi>
     </msub>
     <mo>∝</mo>
     <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
     <msub>
      <mover accent="true">
       <mi>ε</mi>
       <mo>¯</mo>
      </mover>
      <mrow>
       <mi>i</mi>
       <mi>i</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
     <mo>−</mo>
     <msub>
      <mover accent="true">
       <mi>ε</mi>
       <mo>¯</mo>
      </mover>
      <mrow>
       <mi>j</mi>
       <mi>j</mi>
      </mrow>
     </msub>
     <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> at 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm80">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>ϕ</mi>
     <mo stretchy="false">→</mo>
     <mn>1</mn>
     <mo>/</mo>
     <mn>2</mn>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>. It needs to be mentioned that the given notion of the effective 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm81">
   <mrow>
    <mi>χ</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> is perfectly harmonious with that from Sanchez–Lacombe theory [
 <xref rid="B36-polymers-11-01081" ref-type="bibr">36</xref>,
 <xref rid="B37-polymers-11-01081" ref-type="bibr">37</xref>,
 <xref rid="B38-polymers-11-01081" ref-type="bibr">38</xref>].
</p>
